Ask HN: Anyone know a tool for historical rottentomatoes ranking
text:
I have twice in the past week encountered a reason to look up what the historical rottentomatoes ranking of a movie was - or what it was or would have been (if RT had existed) when it first came out.

As an example Speed is now rated 94% fresh which I believe is a totally appropriate rating, but I doubt if that is what it rated when it first came out. I guess could take the earliest reviews and derive a rating for the oldest years it has - it has one for 1994, so if I took just the ratings for 2000 and 94 it seems that the rating is 84% fresh, but I'm wondering if there is a more advanced tool/access to more extensive datasource than what I could do myself just going over older reviews on rottentomatoes, or if there is already an imitation of what I am discussing - that is to say something that will give you how fresh something was in a particular year?

title: Ask HN: Which organizations are the best at software development?
text:
Yes, one can name Google or Uber as examples of places where great software development* takes place, but I'm curious what the HN community's take is on what other, non-obvious organizations or teams do this as well.

*I define great software development as those that produce the best outcomes compared to others. I think of rapid development/release, testable code, high-functioning teams, not only following best practices but creating innovating software as well.
